<br>
Other than that, assist your tank, and then press f8 or click from several different angles *and* watch keep watching your target's health. if you pick the same npc name, but with a different health level, then you have a different target. Combine that with watching if he's not mezzed already by looking at it's blinking name. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=samildanachjownes>Samildanach Jownes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 1:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm44.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=206.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> re:New to chanting</span><hr size=1> The following are general suggestions. Part of the fun in being an enchanter is having to adapt to your situation, often at very short notice so don't take everything here as gospel by any means:<br>
<br>
1. Outside View<br>
<br>
Often it can be more beneficial to move the camera around than yourself . Hit F9 to toggle to an external view you like and position the camera such that you can see your group from the maximum possible distance. You can then hold the right mouse button down to scan the area about your group security camera style. This is great for spotting adds and you get to impress your group (who are most likely playing in first person view)  by mezzing adds before they've seen them. It can be nice if you can have the camera positioned so that you are &quot;looking over the shoulder&quot; of the puller as they run in each time too. This often allows you to get one or two mobs mezzed from the back of a train as they run past the camera before the puller has reached the camp, although be ready for social aggro from the unmezzed ones if you mez this early.<br>
<br>
2. Stand behind the main tank:<br>
<br>
If you're having trouble targetting mobs that are stacked on top of each other try standing directly behind the main tank and assisting them to get the target's health bar. Wait for them to hit the target a couple of times. Each hit will knock it back slightly (this will be more pronounced if pets are involved or weapon procs are firing). Then hit F8 to target the closest mob and see if the health bar you get differs from the main one. Chances are, it won't be the main target anymore. Mez away if this is the case. <br>
<br>
2. Use your stuns:<br>
<br>
If you're comfortable that you won't get too many resists, make liberal use of your Color stun series to buy yourself time to target adds. At 24th you will have two and i'd recomend keeping them both memorised.  When a pull comes in step up in behind the tank and stun them all with a quick Flux/Shift sequence. This gives you a few seconds to click around for a mob whose health bar isn't moving (assuming everyone is assisting properly...) and mez it. Repeat as needed: Flux/Shift/Mez. This works well with Tip 1, particularly if you aren't confident in your tank surviving long enough to get the adds locked down. Be wary of doing this on massive pulls until you hit level 44 and get your 3rd Color stun (and even then you may die unless you're significantly higher level than your opponents) but it can be great for 2-4 mob pulls. <br>
<br>
3. AE mez:<br>
<br>
If you have the room to stay out of it's range, AE mez is always handy as already suggested. That said, it's still worth learning how to control a crowd without out it since you'll lose this particular tool at later levels (specifically when you start hunting mobs in the mid 50s and higher).<br>
<br>
4. Skeletons:<br>
<br>
These can be a real pain to target sometimes. I usually find either the feet or the head (depending on the particular model) are the best places to click when trying to target them.<br>
<br>
5. Mezzing the puller's target<br>
<br>
If you discuss it with your puller (and tank if they are two different people) you can agree to mez the main target *first* and let the tank pick the next one. Most of the time this is more trouble than it's worth (particularly if your puller is a shadowknight or necro using the darkness line) but there are occasionally situations where you might want to do it.<br>
<br>
6. A co-operative tank<br>
<br>
A good tank can make an average enchanter look like a great one with a little help. The main thing they can do to aid you is to pull the main target a short distance away from it's friends each time a mob is mezzed. Done correctly, this will leave all the adds nicely spread out for remezzing.<br>
